<!-- Meta Tags for True Anthem -->
<meta name="socialpost1" content="Two men promised a $1.1 million 3D printer could fix this town’s housing crisis. To this day, the one duplex it printed still isn’t finished. A $590,000 deposit for the printer was forfeited. And the more we asked questions, the weirder things got." />
<meta name="socialpost2" content="When I first met Jamie Hayes, the car dealer who bought the 3D printer for the housing project, I didn’t know his company had abandoned a $590K deposit — or that there was no real housing plan. I didn’t know Hayes’ firm had drawn the FBI’s attention." />
<meta name="socialpost3" content="The company behind the 3D-printed housing deal has been Illinois state Sen. Dale Fowler’s largest source of campaign donations since 2021, excluding PACs. Its final donation of $6,500 was made to him 5 days after the project’s groundbreaking party." />
<meta name="socialpost4" content="When Cairo, Illinois, announced 3D-printed homes as its first affordable housing project in decades, Kaneesha Mallory imagined a bedroom her 6-year-old could finally call her own. Then the work stopped before the first duplex was even finished." />
<meta name="socialpost5" content="For months, an employee managing the 3D-printed housing project told city leaders it would secure financing for 29 remaining homes. But how? The city attorney couldn’t get an answer. The housing task force never got a project rendering." />
